  "description": "Mathematics is a grouping of sciences, including geometry, algebra, and calculus, that study quantity, structure, space, and change.\u00a0 Mathematics concentrators at Brown can explore these concepts through the department\u2019s broad course offerings and flexible concentration requirements. The concentration leads to either the Bachelor of Arts or Bachelor of Science degree (the latter is strongly recommended for students interested in pursuing graduate study in mathematics or related fields). Concentrators begin their learning with multivariable calculus, linear algebra, and abstract algebra. Beyond these prerequisites, students take a variety of advanced topics on the 1000 level based on their interests. After sufficient preparation and with permission of the instructor, students may also take courses on the 2000 level. Students also have the option of completing a thesis project. Concentrators in mathematics should complete the prerequisites by the end of their sophomore year.It is strongly recommended that students takeMATH\u00a01010before takingMATH\u00a01630, (formerly MATH 1130).",
